{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cf6db3c7-19f6-4905-a500-1d61fa92f757","content":"Use **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\nHere's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the **latest** workload versions compatible with your current SDK. After a .NET SDK update, your existing workload packages may no longer match the new SDK band, so this brings everything into alignment.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — **reinstalls** the same workload versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything. If the issue is a version mismatch with a newer SDK, repair won't help.\n\n**TL;DR:** SDK changed → run `dotnet workload update`. Installation got corrupted → run `dotnet workload repair`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f72e0c14-917a-437f-9e9f-68165d0422d5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build.\n\nThis is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task. I can answer directly.\n\n- `dotnet workload update` — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads for the current SDK band. This is what you want after a SDK update, because the workloads need to match the new SDK version.\n- `dotnet workload repair` — reinstalls the *same* versions of workloads that are already recorded, fixing corrupted or incomplete installations. \n\nSince `repair` doesn't actually upgrade anything, `dotnet workload update` is the right move here to align the workloads with the new SDK version.","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"7FC3:2E9A50:5D8DE9D:665E31C:69F155ED"},"id":"1f841111-1a5d-483f-9dc9-0c7de8d853c1","timestamp":"2026-04-29T00:51:04.636Z","parentId":"b1b3888c-6592-4951-9d24-3bd59a1c4f7b"}
